{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565720"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:31:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:31:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18283"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18283"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.73,0.02,0.19,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10997"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104545"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10997"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18283"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86874"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"253"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"5624"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25545"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37670"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104545"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe surgical intern is asked to review a 68-year-old woman on the general surgical ward shortly after her return following a lengthy open cholecystectomy. She reports increasing shortness of breath and chest discomfort. She has a history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. Her regular medications include metformin and perindopril. She has received appropriate post-operative analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There are reduced breath sounds and dullness to percussion at both lung bases. Her calves are soft and non-tender. Her surgical wound appears clean and dry. Chest X-ray shows poor lung expansion, with bibasal collapse and no evidence of effusion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest tube insertion","Mobilisation and chest physiotherapy","Therapeutic anticoagulation","Continuous positive airway pressure","Empiric antibiotics"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with post-operative respiratory symptoms due to bibasal atelectasis, a common complication following upper abdominal surgery - especially when the surgery is prolonged, via laparotomy and in an elderly patient. The diagnosis is supported by the clinical findings of reduced breath sounds and basal dullness, along with confirmatory chest X-ray findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMobilisation and chest physiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. This helps re-expand collapsed alveoli through deep breathing exercises, incentive spirometry, and physical movement. Early mobilisation also helps prevent venous stasis and reduces the risk of post-operative complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous positive airway pressure \u003C/strong\u003E(CPAP)  may help maintain alveolar recruitment but should not be the first-line treatment. While it can be useful in severe cases or when other measures fail, initial management should focus on more conservative measures like mobilisation and physiotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETherapeutic anticoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if pulmonary embolism was suspected. However, the clinical features (bibasal changes on examination and X-ray) and absence of calf signs make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpiric antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated as there are no features suggesting pneumonia such as fever, purulent sputum, or consolidation on chest X-ray. The changes are attributed to atelectasis - though the patient is at risk of developing a pneumonia if the atelectasis is not addressed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest tube insertion\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for managing a pleural effusion or pneumothorax, neither of which are present on the chest X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early recognition of post-operative atelectasis is crucial as it is a common cause of post-operative respiratory distress.","Chest physiotherapy and early mobilisation are key interventions in preventing and treating post-operative atelectasis.","Supplemental oxygen alone does not address the underlying cause of post-operative atelectasis."],"references":["Grott K, Chauhan S, Sanghavi DK, et al. Atelectasis. [Updated 2024 Feb 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545316/","Karcz M, Papadakos PJ. Respiratory complications in the postanesthesia care unit: a review of pathophysiological mechanisms. Can J Respir Ther. 2013 Winter;49(4):21\u201329. PMID: 26078599; PMCID: PMC4456822. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4456822"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86874"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18283"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86874"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T15:00:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-07T13:46:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10997"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104545"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/253"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Atelectasis","synonyms":["Pulmonary atelectasis"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:04+09:30","update